<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - CAB - TILT: 9600 AND 9700 SLEEPER AND NON-SLEEPER CABS -
        CAB TILTING PROCEDURE
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec id="hl1600601">
        <title>CAB TILTING PROCEDURE</title>
        <svcsubsecinfo>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Failure to follow proper procedures may result in serious personal injury, death or property
                        damage.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>To prevent possible cab nosing over, do not remove rear wheels or reduce weight on rear of
                        chassis while cab is at full tilt position.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Provide sufficient cab clearance in front of cab before raising cab. Cab will free fall to
                        fully tilted position when raised past the balance point (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1600606">Figure 6</hotlnk>). To stop the cab free fall, move pump valve lever
                        to the "LOWER" position.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f1600606" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1600606" filename="../figg16/g1600606.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Cab Tilt Positions</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. LATCHED</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. 35 DEGREES (APPROX.)</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. BALANCED</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. FULL TILT IS 70 DEGREES (APPROX.)</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. FREE FALL (NEW SYSTEM)</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubsecinfo>
    </svcsubsec>
